00:01:03.900 --> 00:01:08.739
Over the last year or so, the coding world has really changed. Code is increasingly written

00:01:08.739 --> 00:01:14.739
by or with the help of coding agents. And working with data involves writing code, but

00:01:14.739 --> 00:01:19.980
it isn't really the same as pure software engineering. Data scientists, researchers,

00:01:19.980 --> 00:01:24.260
analysts, et cetera, have particular needs and constraints because your job is not just

00:01:24.260 --> 00:01:31.699
to build tools, but also to develop an accurate understanding of the world through your data.

00:01:31.699 --> 00:01:37.139
And because of this, data scientists need coding agents built for them. At Posit, we've

00:01:37.139 --> 00:01:43.260
been making coding assistants or agents for people who work with data since about 2024,

00:01:43.260 --> 00:01:47.820
which is really as long as this was even a feasible option. And today, we're going to

00:01:47.820 --> 00:01:53.940
talk about our latest, most advanced and mature agent, Posit Assistant. Posit Assistant,

00:01:53.940 --> 00:01:58.739
as you'll see in a bit, is both a general purpose coding agent and a specialized data

00:01:58.739 --> 00:02:06.540
analysis agent. And it lives right in our studio and Positron.

00:02:06.540 --> 00:02:10.740
If you've been following Posit's agent development, you might have noticed an evolution in our

00:02:10.740 --> 00:02:17.339
thought process about agents for data science. We've gone from caution and even some pessimism

00:02:17.860 --> 00:02:22.660
to where we are today, which is confident in the usefulness of these tools and in our

00:02:22.660 --> 00:02:29.539
ability to make them. So in August of 2025, we released DataBot, which is an experimental

00:02:29.539 --> 00:02:35.380
exploratory data analysis agent available in Positron. And we were really excited, but

00:02:35.380 --> 00:02:42.539
also worried about the risks of DataBot incorrectly analyzing data. And so DataBot was purposely

00:02:42.539 --> 00:02:48.059
constrained just to EDA and also released wrapped under several layers of warning.

00:02:48.059 --> 00:02:53.179
We even had a literal caution sign as the image of one of our blog posts.

00:02:53.179 --> 00:02:58.100
So we went from releasing DataBot in August of 2025 like this to where we are today with

00:02:58.100 --> 00:03:03.940
Posit Assistant and the Posit AI service, which I think is a much more confident, optimistic

00:03:03.940 --> 00:03:11.699
place. So what changed? The first thing is that the models really have improved dramatically.

00:03:11.699 --> 00:03:16.660
This makes the possibility of catastrophic mistakes generally go down and also just means

00:03:16.660 --> 00:03:21.699
that the models are much more useful as agents today. Model improvement is sort of like the

00:03:21.699 --> 00:03:27.539
rising tide that lifts all the boats of agent behavior. We've also taken everything that

00:03:27.539 --> 00:03:32.500
we've learned from our past experiments, including with Positron Assistant and DataBot, as well

00:03:32.500 --> 00:03:36.820
as what we find useful with general purpose coding agents like Cloud Code. We've taken

00:03:36.820 --> 00:03:41.860
all of that learning and put it into Posit Assistant. And finally, I think our perspective

00:03:41.860 --> 00:03:46.580
on risk has shifted slightly. We're definitely still worried and careful about models making

00:03:46.580 --> 00:03:52.020
mistakes with real world consequences, but there is risk on the other side as well. At

00:03:52.020 --> 00:03:57.660
this point, these tools are really too useful to ignore and you, our users, do important

00:03:57.660 --> 00:04:01.779
work and you deserve access to the state of the art.

